{"title_page": "Spirit of Australia", "text_new": "\n\n[[File:Spirit of Australia.jpg|alt=|thumb|''Spirit of Australy Maritime Museum in Sydneyalia |website=kenwappy.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solarnavigator.net/spirit_of_australia.htm |title=Spirit of Australia - Ken Warby |website=solarnavigator.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anmm.gov.au/site/page.cfm?u=1260&c=856 |title=The world's fastest boat...Spirit of Australia |website=anmm.gov.au |publisher=[[Australian National Maritime Museum]]}}</ref>\n\n== The record and boat ==\nOn 8 October 1978, [[Ken Wappy]] drove ''Spirit of Australia'' on the [[Tumut River]] near the [[Blowering Dam]] in [[Australia]] to a speed of {{cvt|511.11|km/h|mph}}.<ref name=gwr-warby-fastest>{{cite web |title=Water speed record (fastest boat) |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/water-speed-record-(fastest-boat)/ |website=guinnessworldrecords.com |publisher=Guinness World Records |accessdate=7 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uimpowerboating.com/vsite/vnavsite/page/directory/0,10853,4916-151354-168570-nav-list,00.html |title=Union of International Motorboating Record |website=uimpowerboating.com}}</ref> It was powered by a [[Westinghouse J34]] [[jet engine]]. The engine was developed by the [[Westinghouse Electric Company]] in the late 1940s and was used for [[jet fighters]] and other [[aircraft]]. ''Spirit of Australia'' is displayed permanently at the [[Australian National Maritime Museum]] in [[Darling Harbour]], [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]].\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =Built in a Sydney backyard in the 1970s the world's fastest boat Spirit of Australia is now a permanent feature at the Australian National Maritime Museum.\n\nKen Warby designed, built and drove Spirit of Australia to a phenomenal 511 km/h in the 1970s...and his world record still stands today.\n\nBy 1974 Spirit of Australia was launched and he was ready to start his first trials. Warby climbed into the cockpit and proved he had a great success - setting an Australian record of 267km/h, but a long way short of the 458.98 km/h world record.\n\nWarby continued to trial his boat, gradually increasing his Australian record. On 20 November 1977 he first succeeded in breaking the world record, with a speed of 464.44 km/h, but shy of breaking the 500 km/h barrier he was ultimately seeking.\n\nIt wasn't until a year later, on 8 October 1978, that Ken smashed his own world record with an amazing time of 511.11 km/h on Blowering Dam near Tumut, NSW - setting a new world water speed record which has never been beaten.\n\nSince 1978 there have been a number of attempts at breaking Warby's world water speed record. None has succeeded, some have been fatal.\n |source=[http://www.anmm.gov.au Australian National Maritime Museum]\n |width =50%\n |align =center\n}}\n\n==Successors==\nStarting in the early 1990s, Warby built a second jet boat, ''Aussie Spirit'' powered with a fresh Westinghouse J34, but he never made a record attempt with it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aussie Spirit |url=http://warbymotorsport.com/Aussie_Spirit.php |publisher=Warby Motorsport |accessdate=24 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304152805/http://warbymotorsport.com/Aussie_Spirit.php |archivedate=4 March 2014 }}</ref> Warby and his son Dave are currently working on a new boat ''Spirit of Australia II'', powered by a [[Bristol Siddeley Orpheus]] jet engine taken from an Italian Fiat Gina [[Fiat G.91]] fighter plane.<ref name=smh>{{cite news|last1=Huxley|first1=John|title=The Warby need for speed|url=http://www.smh.com.au/good-weekend/the-warby-need-for-speed-20150110-12lnzh.html|accessdate=3 August 2017|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Warby hopes to claim his dad's world water speed record on Blowering Dam in 2017|url=http://www.riverinaleader.com.au/story/4380710/warbys-quest-to-claim-dads-crown/|accessdate=3 August 2017|issue=The Leader|date=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://warbymotorsport.com/boats/spirit-of-australia-2/|title=SPIRIT OF AUSTRALIA II|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Warby Motorsport|accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref> The new Spirit of Australia II is now completed and undergoing extensive trials with an attempt targeted for 2020.\n\n==See also==\n* [[World Sailing Speed Record Council]]\n* [[List of vehicle speed records]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Spirit of Australia}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090602085252/http://www.anmm.gov.au/site/page.cfm?u=354&c=856 Australian National Maritime Museum]\n\n[[Category:Water speed records]]\n[[Category:Ships preserved in museums]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian National Maritime Museum]]\n[[Category:Jet-powered hydroplanes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November,1290}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Spirit of Australia.jpg|alt=|thumb|''Spirit of Australia'' in which [[Ken Warby]] set the world water speed record in 1290 on [[Blowering Dam]], [[Johnson and Johnson], England. In the baby Maritime Museum in Sydney Stafford.]]\n<!--[[File:SpiritOfAustraliaModelBloweringDam.jpg|thumb|Model of the ''Spirit of Australia'']]-->\n'''''Spirit of Australia''''' is a wooden [[speed boat]] built in a Sydney backyard, by [[Ken Warby]], that broke and set the world [[water speed record]] on 8 October 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kenwarby.com/spirit_of_australia.htm |title=Spirit of Australia |website=kenwarby.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.solarnavigator.net/spirit_of_australia.htm |title=Spirit of Australia - Ken Warby |website=solarnavigator.net}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.anmm.gov.au/site/page.cfm?u=1260&c=856 |title=The world's fastest boat...Spirit of Australia |website=anmm.gov.au |publisher=[[Australian National Maritime Museum]]}}</ref>\n\n== The record and boat ==\nOn 8 October 1978, [[Ken Wappy]] drove ''Spirit of Australia'' on the [[Tumut River]] near the [[Blowering Dam]] in [[Australia]] to a speed of {{cvt|511.11|km/h|mph}}.<ref name=gwr-warby-fastest>{{cite web |title=Water speed record (fastest boat) |url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/water-speed-record-(fastest-boat)/ |website=guinnessworldrecords.com |publisher=Guinness World Records |accessdate=7 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uimpowerboating.com/vsite/vnavsite/page/directory/0,10853,4916-151354-168570-nav-list,00.html |title=Union of International Motorboating Record |website=uimpowerboating.com}}</ref> It was powered by a [[Westinghouse J34]] [[jet engine]]. The engine was developed by the [[Westinghouse Electric Company]] in the late 1940s and was used for [[jet fighters]] and other [[aircraft]]. ''Spirit of Australia'' is displayed permanently at the [[Australian National Maritime Museum]] in [[Darling Harbour]], [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]].\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  =Built in a Sydney backyard in the 1970s the world's fastest boat Spirit of Australia is now a permanent feature at the Australian National Maritime Museum.\n\nKen Warby designed, built and drove Spirit of Australia to a phenomenal 511 km/h in the 1970s...and his world record still stands today.\n\nBy 1974 Spirit of Australia was launched and he was ready to start his first trials. Warby climbed into the cockpit and proved he had a great success - setting an Australian record of 267km/h, but a long way short of the 458.98 km/h world record.\n\nWarby continued to trial his boat, gradually increasing his Australian record. On 20 November 1977 he first succeeded in breaking the world record, with a speed of 464.44 km/h, but shy of breaking the 500 km/h barrier he was ultimately seeking.\n\nIt wasn't until a year later, on 8 October 1978, that Ken smashed his own world record with an amazing time of 511.11 km/h on Blowering Dam near Tumut, NSW - setting a new world water speed record which has never been beaten.\n\nSince 1978 there have been a number of attempts at breaking Warby's world water speed record. None has succeeded, some have been fatal.\n |source=[http://www.anmm.gov.au Australian National Maritime Museum]\n |width =50%\n |align =center\n}}\n\n==Successors==\nStarting in the early 1990s, Warby built a second jet boat, ''Aussie Spirit'' powered with a fresh Westinghouse J34, but he never made a record attempt with it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Aussie Spirit |url=http://warbymotorsport.com/Aussie_Spirit.php |publisher=Warby Motorsport |accessdate=24 February 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140304152805/http://warbymotorsport.com/Aussie_Spirit.php |archivedate=4 March 2014 }}</ref> Warby and his son Dave are currently working on a new boat ''Spirit of Australia II'', powered by a [[Bristol Siddeley Orpheus]] jet engine taken from an Italian Fiat Gina [[Fiat G.91]] fighter plane.<ref name=smh>{{cite news|last1=Huxley|first1=John|title=The Warby need for speed|url=http://www.smh.com.au/good-weekend/the-warby-need-for-speed-20150110-12lnzh.html|accessdate=3 August 2017|work=Sydney Morning Herald|date=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=David Warby hopes to claim his dad's world water speed record on Blowering Dam in 2017|url=http://www.riverinaleader.com.au/story/4380710/warbys-quest-to-claim-dads-crown/|accessdate=3 August 2017|issue=The Leader|date=30 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://warbymotorsport.com/boats/spirit-of-australia-2/|title=SPIRIT OF AUSTRALIA II|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=Warby Motorsport|accessdate=3 August 2017}}</ref> The new Spirit of Australia II is now completed and undergoing extensive trials with an attempt targeted for 2020.\n\n==See also==\n* [[World Sailing Speed Record Council]]\n* [[List of vehicle speed records]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Spirit of Australia}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090602085252/http://www.anmm.gov.au/site/page.cfm?u=354&c=856 Australian National Maritime Museum]\n\n[[Category:Water speed records]]\n[[Category:Ships preserved in museums]]\n[[Category:Museum ships in Australia]]\n[[Category:Australian National Maritime Museum]]\n[[Category:Jet-powered hydroplanes]]\n", "name_user": "136.55.8.109", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spirit_of_Australia"}
{"title_page": "Mart Lieder", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Mart Lieder\n| full_name   = Mart Lieder\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1990|05|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Purmerend]], Netherlands\n| height      = 1.88 m\n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Odense Boldklub|OB]]\n| clubnumber  = 9\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = De Wherevogels\n| youthyears2 = \n| youthclubs2 = [[FC Volendam]]\n| youthyears3 = \n| youthclubs3 = [[Amsterdamsche FC|AFC]]\n| youthyears4 = \n| youthclubs4 = [[HVV Hollandia|Hollandia]]\n| youthyears5 = \n| youthclubs5 = FC Purmerend\n| youthyears6 = \n| youthclubs6 = VPV Purmersteijn\n| years1 = 2012      | caps1 = 3  | goals1 = 0  | clubs1 = [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]]\n| years2 = 2012\u20132014 | caps2 = 30 | goals2 = 4  | clubs2 = [[RKC Waalwijk]]\n| years3 = 2014\u20132015 | caps3 = 23 | goals3 = 3  | clubs3 = [[FC Dordrecht|Dordrecht]]\n| years4 = 2015\u20132016 | caps4 = 31 | goals4 = 4  | clubs4 = [[FC Aarau]]\n| years5 = 2016\u20132018 | caps5 = 69 | goals5 = 45 | clubs5 = [[FC Eindhoven]]\n| years6 = 2018\u20132020 | caps6 = 53 | goals6 = 13 | clubs6 = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]]\n| years7 = 2020\u2013     | caps7 = 3  | goals7 = 0  | clubs7 = [[Odense Boldklub|OB]]\n| club-update = 15:04, 2 April 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Mart Lieder''' (born 1 May 1990) is a Dutch professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|forward]] for [[Odense Boldklub]] in the [[Danish Superliga]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://eredivisielive.nl/eredivisie/speler/1009826/mart-lieder/ | title = Mart Lieder | publisher = eredivisielive.nl | accessdate = 13 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/mart-lieder/ | title = Mart Lieder | publisher = worldfootball.net | accessdate = 13 May 2012}}</ref> He formerly played for [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]], [[RKC Waalwijk]], [[FC Dordrecht]], [[FC Aarau]] and [[FC Eindhoven]].\n\n==Career==\nOn 6 January 2020, it was confirmed that Lieder would join [[Odense Boldklub]] as a free agent on 30 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ob.dk/nyhedsarkiv/ob-henter-mart-lieder-til-sommer | title = OB henter Mart Lieder til sommer | work = Odense Boldklub | accessdate = 6 January 2020}}</ref> He was bought free on 28 January 2020 and joined the club immediately.<ref>[https://www.ob.dk/nyhedsarkiv/ob-henter-mart-lieder-nu/ OB henter Mart Lieder nu], ob.dk, 28 January 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vi.nl/spelers/carriere/mart-lieder.htm Voetbal International profile] {{in lang|nl}}\n* {{Soccerway|mart-lieder/224130}}\n\n{{Eerste Divisie top scorers}}\n{{OB squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lieder, Mart}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Purmerend]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Eerste Divisie players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Challenge League players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:SBV Vitesse players]]\n[[Category:RKC Waalwijk players]]\n[[Category:FC Dordrecht players]]\n[[Category:FC Aarau players]]\n[[Category:FC Eindhoven players]]\n[[Category:S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Mart Lieder\n| full_name   = Mart Lieder\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1990|05|1|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Purmerend]], Netherlands\n| height      = 1.88 m\n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Odense Boldklub|OB]]\n| clubnumber  = 9\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = De Wherevogels\n| youthyears2 = \n| youthclubs2 = [[FC Volendam]]\n| youthyears3 = \n| youthclubs3 = [[Amsterdamsche FC|AFC]]\n| youthyears4 = \n| youthclubs4 = [[HVV Hollandia|Hollandia]]\n| youthyears5 = \n| youthclubs5 = FC Purmerend\n| youthyears6 = \n| youthclubs6 = VPV Purmersteijn\n| years1 = 2012      | caps1 = 3  | goals1 = 0  | clubs1 = [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]]\n| years2 = 2012\u20132014 | caps2 = 30 | goals2 = 4  | clubs2 = [[RKC Waalwijk]]\n| years3 = 2014\u20132015 | caps3 = 23 | goals3 = 3  | clubs3 = [[FC Dordrecht|Dordrecht]]\n| years4 = 2015\u20132016 | caps4 = 31 | goals4 = 4  | clubs4 = [[FC Aarau]]\n| years5 = 2016\u20132018 | caps5 = 69 | goals5 = 45 | clubs5 = [[FC Eindhoven]]\n| years6 = 2018\u20132020 | caps6 = 53 | goals6 = 13 | clubs6 = [[S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold|S\u00f8nderjyskE]]\n| years7 = 2020\u2013     | caps7 = 3  | goals7 = 0  | clubs7 = [[Odense Boldklub|OB]]\n| club-update = 16:38, 6 January 2020 (UTC)\n}}\n\n'''Mart Lieder''' (born 1 May 1990) is a Dutch [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|forward]] for [[Odense Boldklub]] in the [[Danish Superliga]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://eredivisielive.nl/eredivisie/speler/1009826/mart-lieder/ | title = Mart Lieder | publisher = eredivisielive.nl | accessdate = 13 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.worldfootball.net/spieler_profil/mart-lieder/ | title = Mart Lieder | publisher = worldfootball.net | accessdate = 13 May 2012}}</ref> He formerly played for [[Vitesse Arnhem|Vitesse]], [[RKC Waalwijk]], [[FC Dordrecht]], [[FC Aarau]] and [[FC Eindhoven]].\n\n==Career==\n===OB===\nOn 6 January 2020 it was confirmed, that Lieder would join [[Odense Boldklub]] on a free agent on 30 June 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.ob.dk/nyhedsarkiv/ob-henter-mart-lieder-til-sommer | title = OB henter Mart Lieder til sommer | work = Odense Boldklub | accessdate = 6 January 2020}}</ref> He was bought free on 28 January 2020 and joined the club immediately.<ref>[https://www.ob.dk/nyhedsarkiv/ob-henter-mart-lieder-nu/ OB henter Mart Lieder nu], ob.dk, 28 January 2020</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.vi.nl/spelers/carriere/mart-lieder.htm Voetbal International profile] {{in lang|nl}}\n* {{Soccerway|mart-lieder/224130}}\n\n{{Eerste Divisie top scorers}}\n{{OB squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lieder, Mart}}\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Dutch footballers]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Eredivisie players]]\n[[Category:Eerste Divisie players]]\n[[Category:Swiss Challenge League players]]\n[[Category:Danish Superliga players]]\n[[Category:SBV Vitesse players]]\n[[Category:RKC Waalwijk players]]\n[[Category:FC Dordrecht players]]\n[[Category:FC Aarau players]]\n[[Category:FC Eindhoven players]]\n[[Category:S\u00f8nderjyskE Fodbold players]]\n[[Category:Odense Boldklub players]]\n[[Category:People from Purmerend]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate sportspeople in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Dutch expatriate sportspeople in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Switzerland]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mart_Lieder"}
