{"title_page": "National University of Technology", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Infobox university\n|name         = National University of Technology\n|image_size   = \n|motto        = Leading towards progress and excellence\n|established  = 2018\n|type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment    = \n|chancellor   = [[President of Pakistan]]\n|rector       = Engineer Khalid Asghar\n|students     = 500+\n|undergrad    = 325\n|postgrad     = \n|coor         = \n|city         = [[Islamabad]]\n|province     = \n|country      = [[Pakistan]]\n|campus       = \n|website      = {{URL|nutech.edu.pk}}\n|staff        = \n|faculty      = \n|affiliations = [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)]] [Pakistan Engineering Council] [NCEAC]\n|image_name   = NUTECH logo.png\n}}\nThe '''National University of Technology''' ('''NUTECH)''', is a public university located in Islamabad, Pakistan<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1353106|title=NA body passes university of technology bill|first=A|last=Reporter|date=22 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref>. The university is a federally chartered institution recognized by Higher Education Commission (HEC), Pakistan<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://hec.gov.pk/english/universities/Pages/Islamabad/NUTECH.aspx|title=HEC Recognizes NUTCEH|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nIn August 2017, a bill was passed by the [https://na.gov.pk National Assembly of Pakistan] to establish a technological university under ''The National University of Technology Bill, 2017''<ref name=\"auto\" />. NUTECH is part of the consolidation effort by [https://most.gov.pk Ministry of Science and Technology (MOST)], Pakistan for progress in the areas of Human Resource Development; Transfer of Technology from R&D Institutions and Universities to the Industry; Food and Agriculture; Analytical Centres for Industrial Analysis, Industrialization, Health, Electronics, Ocean Resources, New Materials, Biotechnology, Textiles and Pharmaceutical<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://most.gov.pk|title=Institutions under MOST, Pakistan|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== NUTECH Industrial  Symposium ==\nNUTECH conducted a day-long \u201cNUTECH-Pak Swiss Old Boys Association (OBA)-Pak Industry Joint Collaboration Symposium\u201d on Feb 21, 2020 which aimed to bridge the gap between academia and industry of the country<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/21-Feb-2020/nutech-conducts-symposium|title=NUTECH conducts symposium|date=2020-02-20|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<br />\n\n{{coord missing|Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National University of Technology}}\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-stub}}\n", "text_old": "Public university in Islamabad, Pakistan.Run by FWO which is the sector of Pakistan Army-Armed University-And Also under the control of MOST\n{{Infobox university\n|name         = National University of Technology\n|image_size   = \n|motto        = Leading towards progress and excellence\n|established  = 2018\n|type         = [[Public university|Public]]\n|endowment    = \n|chancellor   = [[President of Pakistan]]\n|rector       = Engineer Khalid Asghar\n|students     = 500+\n|undergrad    = 325\n|postgrad     = \n|coor         = \n|city         = [[Islamabad]]\n|province     = \n|country      = [[Pakistan]]\n|campus       = \n|website      = {{URL|nutech.edu.pk}}\n|staff        = \n|faculty      = \n|affiliations = [[Higher Education Commission (Pakistan)]] [Pakistan Engineering Council] [NCEAC]\n|image_name   = NUTECH logo.png\n}}\nThe '''National University of Technology''' ('''NUTECH)''', is a public university located in Islamabad, Pakistan<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dawn.com/news/1353106|title=NA body passes university of technology bill|first=A|last=Reporter|date=22 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref>. The university is a federally chartered institution recognized by Higher Education Commission (HEC), Pakistan<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://hec.gov.pk/english/universities/Pages/Islamabad/NUTECH.aspx|title=HEC Recognizes NUTCEH|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\nIn August 2017, a bill was passed by the [https://na.gov.pk National Assembly of Pakistan] to establish a technological university under ''The National University of Technology Bill, 2017''<ref name=\"auto\" />. NUTECH is part of the consolidation effort by [https://most.gov.pk Ministry of Science and Technology (MOST)], Pakistan for progress in the areas of Human Resource Development; Transfer of Technology from R&D Institutions and Universities to the Industry; Food and Agriculture; Analytical Centres for Industrial Analysis, Industrialization, Health, Electronics, Ocean Resources, New Materials, Biotechnology, Textiles and Pharmaceutical<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://most.gov.pk|title=Institutions under MOST, Pakistan|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== NUTECH Industrial  Symposium ==\nNUTECH conducted a day-long \u201cNUTECH-Pak Swiss Old Boys Association (OBA)-Pak Industry Joint Collaboration Symposium\u201d on Feb 21, 2020 which aimed to bridge the gap between academia and industry of the country<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/21-Feb-2020/nutech-conducts-symposium|title=NUTECH conducts symposium|date=2020-02-20|website=The Nation|language=en|access-date=2020-02-23}}</ref>.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}<br />\n\n{{coord missing|Pakistan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:National University of Technology}}\n[[Category:2018 establishments in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Public universities and colleges in Pakistan]]\n\n\n{{Pakistan-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Humcom", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_University_of_Technology"}
{"title_page": "Ben Hardman", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n'''Benedict (Ben) Paul Hardman''' (born 4 August 1964) is an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]] member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from 1999 to 2010, representing the electorate of [[Electoral district of Seymour|Seymour]].\n\nHardman was born in [[Kiama, New South Wales|Kiama]], [[New South Wales]]. He was educated at [[St Peter and Paul Primary School, Kiama|St Peter and Paul Primary School]] and [[St Gregory's College, Campbelltown|St Gregory's College]], [[Campbelltown, New South Wales|Campbelltown]]. He worked as a steward with the Wagga Wagga Leagues Club from 1982 to 1983, and as a clerk for the Wagga Wagga City Council from 1983 to 1986, before moving to [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] to study teaching at the [[University of Ballarat]]. He graduated in 1989, and worked as a teacher at [[Highlands Primary School]] before being appointed principal of [[Flowerdale Primary School]] in 1996, a role he held until his election to parliament.<ref name=\"Re-member: Ben Hardman\">[http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=102 \"Re-member: Ben Hardman\"]. ''[[Parliament of Victoria]]'' Retrieved on 4 May 2009.</ref>\n\nHardman was preselected as the Labor candidate for the state seat of [[Electoral district of Seymour|Seymour]] for the [[1999 Victorian state election|1999 state election]]. Seymour was a Liberal-leaning seat that had been easily held by retiring Liberal minister [[Marie Tehan]], and Hardman was not expected to win; however, amidst the Bracks government's surprise victory he emerged successful, eking out a narrow win on election day. He increased his majority sharply amidst Labor's landslide re-election in [[2002 Victorian state election|2002]], and was again easily re-elected in [[2006 Victorian state election|2006]].<ref name=\"Re-member: Ben Hardman\" /><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/vic/2006/guide/seym.htm \"2006 Victorian Election: Seymour Electorate Profile\"]. ''[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'' Retrieved on 4 May 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.vec.vic.gov.au/state2006resultSeymourDistrict.html \"State Election 2006: Seymour District\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415124637/http://www.vec.vic.gov.au/state2006resultSeymourDistrict.html |date=15 April 2009 }}. ''[[Parliament of Victoria]]'' Retrieved on 4 May 2009.</ref> He was defeated in [[2010 Victorian state election|2010]]. Also my man ben loves corey and his kids\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Electoral district of Seymour|Seymour]] | before=[[Marie Tehan]] | after=[[Cindy McLeish]] | years=1999&ndash;2010}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardman, Ben}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Federation University Australia alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=June 2015}}\n'''Benedict (Ben) Paul Hardman''' (born 4 August 1964) is an [[Australia]]n politician. He was a [[Australian Labor Party (Victorian Branch)|Labor Party]] member of the [[Victorian Legislative Assembly]] from 1999 to 2010, representing the electorate of [[Electoral district of Seymour|Seymour]].\n\nHardman was born in [[Kiama, New South Wales|Kiama]], [[New South Wales]]. He was educated at [[St Peter and Paul Primary School, Kiama|St Peter and Paul Primary School]] and [[St Gregory's College, Campbelltown|St Gregory's College]], [[Campbelltown, New South Wales|Campbelltown]]. He worked as a steward with the Wagga Wagga Leagues Club from 1982 to 1983, and as a clerk for the Wagga Wagga City Council from 1983 to 1986, before moving to [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] to study teaching at the [[University of Ballarat]]. He graduated in 1989, and worked as a teacher at [[Highlands Primary School]] before being appointed principal of [[Flowerdale Primary School]] in 1996, a role he held until his election to parliament.<ref name=\"Re-member: Ben Hardman\">[http://www.parliament.vic.gov.au/re-member/bioregfull.cfm?mid=102 \"Re-member: Ben Hardman\"]. ''[[Parliament of Victoria]]'' Retrieved on 4 May 2009.</ref>\n\nHardman was preselected as the Labor candidate for the state seat of [[Electoral district of Seymour|Seymour]] for the [[1999 Victorian state election|1999 state election]]. Seymour was a Liberal-leaning seat that had been easily held by retiring Liberal minister [[Marie Tehan]], and Hardman was not expected to win; however, amidst the Bracks government's surprise victory he emerged successful, eking out a narrow win on election day. He increased his majority sharply amidst Labor's landslide re-election in [[2002 Victorian state election|2002]], and was again easily re-elected in [[2006 Victorian state election|2006]].<ref name=\"Re-member: Ben Hardman\" /><ref>[http://www.abc.net.au/elections/vic/2006/guide/seym.htm \"2006 Victorian Election: Seymour Electorate Profile\"]. ''[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]]'' Retrieved on 4 May 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.vec.vic.gov.au/state2006resultSeymourDistrict.html \"State Election 2006: Seymour District\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090415124637/http://www.vec.vic.gov.au/state2006resultSeymourDistrict.html |date=15 April 2009 }}. ''[[Parliament of Victoria]]'' Retrieved on 4 May 2009.</ref> He was defeated in [[2010 Victorian state election|2010]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|au-vic-la}}\n{{succession box | title=Member for [[Electoral district of Seymour|Seymour]] | before=[[Marie Tehan]] | after=[[Cindy McLeish]] | years=1999&ndash;2010}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hardman, Ben}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Australian Labor Party members of the Parliament of Victoria]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Victorian Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Federation University Australia alumni]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Babatunde habibi", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Fixed)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ben_Hardman"}
{"title_page": "List of The Good Wife and The Good Fight characters", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of ''The Good Wife'' and ''The Good Fight'' characters}}\n\n''[[The Good Wife]]'' and its spin-off, ''[[The Good Fight]]'', are American [[Legal drama|legal]] and [[Political drama|political]] [[Television program|television series]] produced for [[CBS]] and CBS' [[streaming service]] [[CBS All Access]] respectively, created by [[Robert King (writer)|Robert]] and [[Michelle King]]. ''The Good Wife'' follows the political, professional, and personal life of [[Alicia Florrick]] ([[Julianna Margulies]]), a political \"good wife\" who is thrust back into the workplace after over a decade after her husband, Peter Florrick ([[Chris Noth]]), a local [[Chicago]] [[politician]], is arrested on corruption charged following a highly publicized sex scandal.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The Good Wife - Cast & Crew |url=http://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-good-wife/cast/297522/ |magazine=[[TV Guide]] |access-date=May 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Good Wife (Cast)|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/the-good-wife/cast/|website=TV.com|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Good Wife Cast|url=https://www.cbs.com/shows/the_good_wife/cast/|website=cbs.com|publisher=[[CBS Television]]|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Stanhope|first1=Kate|title='The Good Wife': What's Next for the Cast|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/good-wife-whats-next-cast-892173|website=hollywoodreporter.com|publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=May 9, 2018}}</ref> ''The Good Fight'' follows Alicia's former colleagues [[Diane Lockhart]] ([[Christine Baranski]]) and Lucca Quinn ([[Cush Jumbo]]) contending with political and legal challenges in a [[Trump era|new political environment]] as they continue their careers at a left-wing, African American\u2013owned law firm.\n\n==Main==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrow