rald Kozko\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"9\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| [[Ismael Cruz C\u00f3rdova]]\n| Jimmy Patrick\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Cady Huffman]]\n| Marina Vassel\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"5\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Tim Guinee]]\n| Andrew Wiley\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Kelli Giddish]]\n| Sophia Russo\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\" |\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Elizabeth Reaser]]\n| Tammy Linnata\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\" |\n|-\n| Eric Ruffin\n| Dylan Bishop\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Susan Misner]]\n| Simone Canning\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Lily Rabe]]\n| Petra Moritz\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| Nathan Stark\n| Process Server\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n|-\n| [[Miriam Shor]]\n| Mandy Post\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| Charlie Pollock\n| 'Darkness at Noon' Lead Actor\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\" |\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Linda Lavin]]\n| Joy Grubick\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Ed Asner|Edward Asner]]\n| Guy Redmayne\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"4\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Vanessa L. Williams|Vanessa Williams]]\n| Courtney Paige\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"3\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Megan Hilty]]\n| Holly Westfall\n| colspan=\"6\" style=\"background:#ececec; text-align:center;\"|\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Paul Guilfoyle]]\n| Henry Rindell\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Bernadette Peters]]\n| Lenore Rindell\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Hel\u00e9ne Yorke]]\n| Amy Bresline\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"1\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| Chalia La Tour\n| Yesha Mancini\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Scott Bryce]]\n| Rupert Lennox\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Tom McGowan]]\n| Jax Rindell\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[John Cameron Mitchell]]\n| Felix Staples\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Adam Heller]]\n| Wilbur Dincon\n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{n/a|}}\n|-\n| [[Andrea Martin]]\n| Francesca Lovatelli \n| colspan=\"7\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| colspan=\"2\" {{CRecurring|Recurring|}}\n|-\n| [[Keesha Sharp]]\n| Naomi Nivola\n| colspan=\"8\" {{n/a|}}\n| {{CGuest|Guest}}\n| {{CRecurring|Recurring|}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{The Good Wife}}\n[[Category:The Good Wife characters| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of American drama television series characters|Good Wife]]\n", "name_user": "Araydallas", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecurring", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_The_Good_Wife_and_The_Good_Fight_characters"}
{"title_page": "Calzone", "text_new": "{{short description|Oven-baked folded pizza from Naples}}\n{{distinguish|canzone}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Calzone\n| image            = Wikimania 2016 Deryck day 0 - 07 calzone.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Simple calzone in an Italian pizzeria, cut in half\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Italy]]\n| region           = [[Apulia]], [[Abruzzo]], [[Campania]], [[Calabria]], [[Sicily]], [[Sardegna]], [[Basilicata]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[ravioli]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Ricotta]], [[mozzarella]], salami/ham, parmesan/pecorino\n| variations       = Tomato, provolone, anchovies, olives, onions, chards, minced meat, fish, cabbage\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n{{Pizza}}\nA '''calzone''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|k|\u00e6|l|\u02c8|t|s|o\u028a|n|i|,_|-|n|e\u026a}}, {{IPAc-en|US|k|\u00e6|l|\u02c8|z|o\u028a|n|,_|-|z|o\u028a|n|e\u026a|,_|-|n|i}}, {{IPA-it|kal\u02c8tso\u02d0ne|lang}}; \"stocking\" or \"trouser\")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/calzone |title=dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref> is an Italian oven-baked folded [[pizza]]<ref name=\"oliver\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamieoliver.com/recipes/bread-recipes/calzone |title=calzone &#124; Jamie Oliver &#124; Food &#124; Recipes (UK) |publisher=Jamie Oliver |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref> that originated in [[Naples]]<ref name=\"go785\">Gosetti (1967), p.785</ref> in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecalzonezone.weebly.com/history.html|title=History|website=The CalZone Zone}}</ref> A typical calzone is made from salted bread dough, baked in an oven and is stuffed with [[salami]], ham or vegetables, [[mozzarella]], [[ricotta]] and [[parmigiano reggiano|Parmesan]] or [[pecorino]] cheese, as well as an [[chicken egg|egg]].<ref name=go785/> Different regional variations in or on a calzone can often include other ingredients that are normally associated with pizza toppings. The term usually applies to an oven-baked turnover rather than a fried pastry (i.e. [[panzerotti]]),<ref name=gustoblog>{{cite web|url=http://www.gustoblog.it/post/4249/la-vera-ricetta-dei-panzerotti-pugliesi |title=La vera ricetta dei panzerotti pugliesi |publisher=Gustoblog.it |date=2009-03-03 |accessdate=2015-12-05}}</ref> though ''calzoni'' and ''panzerotti'' are often mistaken for each other.<ref name=gustoblog/><ref>Sarkar, Suhashini (June 29, 2015). [http://www.saveur.com/panzerotti-empanadas-secret-cousin \"Panzerotti: The Empanada\u2019s Italian Cousin\"], ''Saveur''. Retrieved February 13, 2016.</ref><ref>Minchilli, Elizabeth (December 11, 2014). [http://www.elizabethminchilliinrome.com/2014/12/making-panzerotti-in-barivecchia/ \"Making Panzerotti in Barivecchia\"], Elizabeth Minchilli in Rome. Retrieved February 13, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.food.com/recipe/deep-fried-panzerotti-262162 \"Deep Fried Panzerotti\"], food.com. Retrieved February 13, 2016.</ref>\n\nA calzone is somewhat similar to a [[Stromboli (food)|stromboli]]. A calzone is a baked turnover stuffed with pizza ingredients. A stromboli is usually made by rolling up dough with cheese and meat ingredients and is then baked, but it does not generally contain pizza ingredients aside from cheese and Italian meats.  Generally, strombolis do not usually contain [[tomato sauce]], unlike calzones. A calzone is crescent-shaped, and a stromboli is usually shaped like a long cylinder. The distinction between the two is complicated because there is some variation in what constitutes a stromboli.<ref>Shuster, Jim (May 10, 2012). [http://patch.com/california/gilroy/bp--stromboli-verse-the-calzone \"The Stromboli vs. the Calzone\"], ''Gilroy Patch''. Retrieved August 14, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"ChiTrib\">{{cite news |last=Daley |first=Bill |title=Calzone v. Stromboli|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-03-26/features/ct-tribu-daley-question-stromboli-20130326_1_stromboli-calzone-dough |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=March 29, 2013|date=March 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Vadala\">{{Cite web |first=Nick |last=Vadala |date=June 17, 2014 |title=The Stromboli: A Philly Original, Courtesy of Romano's |publisher=[[Philly.com]] |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/food/The-stromboli-A-Philly-original-courtesy-of-Romanos-.html |accessdate=April 16, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Regional variations==\n\n===In Italy===\nSandwich-sized calzones are often sold at Italian lunch counters or by street vendors, because they are easy to eat while standing up or walking.<ref>{{cite book|last=MacKenzie|first=Shea|title=The Pizza Gourmet|year=1995|publisher=Avery Pub. Group|location=Garden City Park, N.Y.|isbn=089529656X|pages=Preface iv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/pizzagourmet00mack}}</ref> Fried versions of the calzone are typically filled with tomato and mozzarella: these are made in [[Apulia]] and are called ''[[panzerotti]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Annamaria Settanni McDonald |url=http://www.justapinch.com/recipes/main-course/italian/panzarotti-pugliese-italian-fried-pizzas.html |title=Puglia panzarotti |publisher=Justapinch.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>\n\nThe Sicilian ''cuddiruni'' or ''cudduruni'' pizza is distantly related to the calzone.  This is a dish stuffed with onions (or sometimes other vegetables, such as potatoes or broccoli), [[Anchovy (food)|anchovies]], olives, cheese and [[mortadella]]; the rolled pizza dough is folded in two over the stuffing and the edges are sealed before the dish is fried.\n\n===In the United States===\nIn the [[United States]], calzones are typically made from pizza dough and stuffed with meats, cheeses, and vegetables. \n\nTraditional calzone dough, consisting of flour, yeast, olive oil, water, and salt, is kneaded and rolled into medium-sized disks.\nEach is then filled with cheeses such as [[ricotta]], mozzarella, [[Parmigiano-Reggiano|Parmesan]], [[provolone]], and other traditional vegetables or meats. The dough is then folded in half over the filling and sealed with an egg mixture in a half-moon shape, or is sometimes shaped into a ball by pinching and sealing all the edges at the top. It is then either baked or fried. \n\nIn some areas, just before serving, they are topped with [[marinara sauce|marinara]] or other traditional sauce, or with a mixture of garlic, olive oil, and parsley.\n\n==Cultural notes==\nIn [[Italy]], as of the 1960s, calzones were popularly believed to be the most efficient type of pizza for home delivery.<ref name=go787>Gosetti (1967), p.787</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[List of Italian dishes]]\n* [[Panzerotti]]\n* [[Pepperoni roll]]\n* [[Pizza puff]]\n* [[Scacciata]]\n* [[Stromboli (food)|Stromboli]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{wiktionary}}\n\n*{{cite book\n | last=Gosetti Della Salda\n | first= Anna\n | title=Le ricette regionali italiane\n | publisher=Solares\n | location= Milano\n | year=1967\n| language=Italian\n}}\n\n{{cheese dishes}}\n{{Street food}}\n\n[[Category:Italian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Savoury pies]]\n[[Category:Street food]]\n[[Category:Pizza styles]]\n[[Category:Calzones|*]]\n[[Category:Stuffed dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Oven-baked folded pizza from Naples}}\n{{distinguish|canzone}}\n{{More citations needed|date=January 2016}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Calzone\n| image            = Wikimania 2016 Deryck day 0 - 07 calzone.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Simple calzone in an Italian pizzeria, cut in half\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[Italy]]\n| region           = [[Apulia]], [[Abruzzo]], [[Campania]], [[Calabria]], [[Sicily]], [[Sardegna]], [[Basilicata]]\n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Turnover (food)|Turnover]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Ricotta]], [[mozzarella]], salami/ham, parmesan/pecorino\n| variations       = Tomato, provolone, anchovies, olives, onions, chards, minced meat, fish, cabbage\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n{{Pizza}}\nA '''calzone''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|k|\u00e6|l|\u02c8|t|s|o\u028a|n|i|,_|-|n|e\u026a}}, {{IPAc-en|US|k|\u00e6|l|\u02c8|z|o\u028a|n|,_|-|z|o\u028a|n|e\u026a|,_|-|n|i}}, {{IPA-it|kal\u02c8tso\u02d0ne|lang}}; \"stocking\" or \"trouser\")<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/calzone |title=dictionary.com |publisher=Dictionary.reference.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref> is an Italian oven-baked folded [[pizza]]<ref name=\"oliver\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jamieoliver.com/recipes/bread-recipes/calzone |title=calzone &#124; Jamie Oliver &#124; Food &#124; Recipes (UK) |publisher=Jamie Oliver |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref> that originated in [[Naples]]<ref name=\"go785\">Gosetti (1967), p.785</ref> in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thecalzonezone.weebly.com/history.html|title=History|website=The CalZone Zone}}</ref> A typical calzone is made from salted bread dough, baked in an oven and is stuffed with [[salami]], ham or vegetables, [[mozzarella]], [[ricotta]] and [[parmigiano reggiano|Parmesan]] or [[pecorino]] cheese, as well as an [[chicken egg|egg]].<ref name=go785/> Different regional variations in or on a calzone can often include other ingredients that are normally associated with pizza toppings. The term usually applies to an oven-baked turnover rather than a fried pastry (i.e. [[panzerotti]]),<ref name=gustoblog>{{cite web|url=http://www.gustoblog.it/post/4249/la-vera-ricetta-dei-panzerotti-pugliesi |title=La vera ricetta dei panzerotti pugliesi |publisher=Gustoblog.it |date=2009-03-03 |accessdate=2015-12-05}}</ref> though ''calzoni'' and ''panzerotti'' are often mistaken for each other.<ref name=gustoblog/><ref>Sarkar, Suhashini (June 29, 2015). [http://www.saveur.com/panzerotti-empanadas-secret-cousin \"Panzerotti: The Empanada\u2019s Italian Cousin\"], ''Saveur''. Retrieved February 13, 2016.</ref><ref>Minchilli, Elizabeth (December 11, 2014). [http://www.elizabethminchilliinrome.com/2014/12/making-panzerotti-in-barivecchia/ \"Making Panzerotti in Barivecchia\"], Elizabeth Minchilli in Rome. Retrieved February 13, 2016.</ref><ref>[http://www.food.com/recipe/deep-fried-panzerotti-262162 \"Deep Fried Panzerotti\"], food.com. Retrieved February 13, 2016.</ref>\n\nA calzone is somewhat similar to a [[Stromboli (food)|stromboli]]. A calzone is a baked turnover stuffed with pizza ingredients. A stromboli is usually made by rolling up dough with cheese and meat ingredients and is then baked, but it does not generally contain pizza ingredients aside from cheese and Italian meats.  Generally, strombolis do not usually contain [[tomato sauce]], unlike calzones. A calzone is crescent-shaped, and a stromboli is usually shaped like a long cylinder. The distinction between the two is complicated because there is some variation in what constitutes a stromboli.<ref>Shuster, Jim (May 10, 2012). [http://patch.com/california/gilroy/bp--stromboli-verse-the-calzone \"The Stromboli vs. the Calzone\"], ''Gilroy Patch''. Retrieved August 14, 2016.</ref><ref name=\"ChiTrib\">{{cite news |last=Daley |first=Bill |title=Calzone v. Stromboli|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-03-26/features/ct-tribu-daley-question-stromboli-20130326_1_stromboli-calzone-dough |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=March 29, 2013|date=March 26, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Vadala\">{{Cite web |first=Nick |last=Vadala |date=June 17, 2014 |title=The Stromboli: A Philly Original, Courtesy of Romano's |publisher=[[Philly.com]] |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/food/The-stromboli-A-Philly-original-courtesy-of-Romanos-.html |accessdate=April 16, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Regional variations==\n\n===In Italy===\nSandwich-sized calzones are often sold at Italian lunch counters or by street vendors, because they are easy to eat while standing up or walking.<ref>{{cite book|last=MacKenzie|first=Shea|title=The Pizza Gourmet|year=1995|publisher=Avery Pub. Group|location=Garden City Park, N.Y.|isbn=089529656X|pages=Preface iv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/pizzagourmet00mack}}</ref> Fried versions of the calzone are typically filled with tomato and mozzarella: these are made in [[Apulia]] and are called ''[[panzerotti]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Annamaria Settanni McDonald |url=http://www.justapinch.com/recipes/main-course/italian/panzarotti-pugliese-italian-fried-pizzas.html |title=Puglia panzarotti |publisher=Justapinch.com |date= |accessdate=2012-11-07}}</ref>\n\nThe Sicilian ''cuddiruni'' or ''cudduruni'' pizza is distantly related to the calzone.  This is a dish stuffed with onions (or sometimes other vegetables, such as potatoes or broccoli), [[Anchovy (food)|anchovies]], olives, cheese and [[mortadella]]; the rolled pizza dough is folded in two over the stuffing and the edges are sealed before the dish is fried.\n\n===In the United States===\nIn the [[United States]], calzones are typically made from pizza dough and stuffed with meats, cheeses, and vegetables. \n\nTraditional calzone dough, consisting of flour, yeast, olive oil, water, and salt, is kneaded and rolled into medium-sized disks.\nEach is then filled with cheeses such as [[ricotta]], mozzarella, [[Parmigiano-Reggiano|Parmesan]], [[provolone]], and other traditional vegetables or meats. The dough is then folded in half over the filling and sealed with an egg mixture in a half-moon shape, or is sometimes shaped into a ball by pinching and sealing all the edges at the top. It is then either baked or fried. \n\nIn some areas, just before serving, they are topped with [[marinara sauce|marinara]] or other traditional sauce, or with a mixture of garlic, olive oil, and parsley.\n\n==Cultural notes==\nIn [[Italy]], as of the 1960s, calzones were popularly believed to be the most efficient type of pizza for home delivery.<ref name=go787>Gosetti (1967), p.787</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* [[List of Italian dishes]]\n* [[Panzerotti]]\n* [[Pepperoni roll]]\n* [[Pizza puff]]\n* [[Scacciata]]\n* [[Stromboli (food)|Stromboli]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{wiktionary}}\n\n*{{cite book\n | last=Gosetti Della Salda\n | first= Anna\n | title=Le ricette regionali italiane\n | publisher=Solares\n | location= Milano\n | year=1967\n| language=Italian\n}}\n\n{{cheese dishes}}\n{{Street food}}\n\n[[Category:Italian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Savoury pies]]\n[[Category:Street food]]\n[[Category:Pizza styles]]\n[[Category:Calzones|*]]\n[[Category:Stuffed dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Beepbop1213", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calzone"}
{"title_page": "White House press corps", "text_new": "{{short description|Group of journalists or correspondents usually stationed at the White House in Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Acting Commissioner of CBP Mark Morgan Speaks to Reporters (48708163577).jpg|thumb|Reporters ask questions at a White House Press Briefing in 2019]]\nThe '''White House press corps''' is the group of [[journalists]], [[correspondents]], or members of the media usually stationed at the [[White House]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], to cover the [[president of the United States]], White House events, and news briefings. Their offices are located in the [[West Wing]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:The Prime Minister of the Czech Republic and Mrs. Monika Babi\u0161ov\u00e1 Visit the White House (40353221263).jpg|thumb|Photographers and videographers in the [[Oval Office]] in 2019]]\n[[File:White House Press Corp outside.jpg|thumb|Semi-permanent setup of press corps on the west end of the north White House lawn, from where live media broadcasts with the White House are typically delivered]]\nThe [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]] or a deputy generally holds a weekday news briefing in the [[James S. Brady Press Briefing Room]]. The room currently seats 49 reporters. Each seat is assigned to a news gathering organization, with the most prominent organizations occupying the first two rows. Reporters who do not have an assigned seat may stand. Often a smaller group of reporters known as the \"White House press pool\" is assembled to report back to their colleagues on events where the venue would make open coverage logistically difficult.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nWhen a new U.S. president is elected, some news organizations change their correspondents, most often to the reporter who had been assigned to cover the new president during the preceding campaign. For example, after the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential campaign]], ABC News moved [[Jake Tapper]], who had covered [[Barack Obama]] during his presidential campaign, to the White House correspondent's position.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==History==\nThe White House press corps had their first duties in the White House in the early 1900s. An [[urban legend]] exists of [[President Theodore Roosevelt]] noticing a group of correspondents in the rain looking for sources for their stories and inviting them into the White House. Subsequent historical research outlines how reporters were able to start with small stories in the White House and then grew their presence and influence over a span of many years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.whca.net/history.htm | title = HISTORY OF THE WHCA | work = WHCA | publisher = White House Correspondents' Association  | date = }}</ref>\n\n==Correspondents==\n\n===Current===\n\nOrdered by [[James S. Brady Press Briefing Room]] seating chart. Reporters listed by last name, unless designated as \"chief\" or \"senior\" by news organization\n\n====Television====\n \n*[[NBC News]]/[[MSNBC]] \u2013 [[Hallie Jackson]], [[Peter Alexander (journalist)|Peter Alexander]], Geoff Bennett<ref>https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/geoff-bennett-joins-nbc-news-as-white-house-correspondent/344528/</ref>, [[Kelly O'Donnell]], [[Shannon Pettypiece]], [[Kristen Welker]] \n*[[Fox News]]/[[Fox Business]] \u2013 [[John Roberts (journalist)|John Roberts]], Blake Burman, [[Kevin Corke]]\n*[[CBS News]]/[[CBSN]]<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/team/</ref> \u2013 [[Major Garrett]], Sara Cook<ref>https://twitter.com/saraecook</ref>, Paula Reid, [[Ben Tracy]]\n*[[ABC News]] \u2013 [[Jonathan Karl]], [[Devin Dwyer]], Katherine Faulders<ref>https://twitter.com/KFaulders</ref>, Jon Garcia<ref>https://twitter.com/GarciaJon</ref>, John R. Parkinson<ref>https://twitter.com/jparkABC</ref>, Jordyn Phelps<ref>https://twitter.com/JordynPhelps</ref>, [[Cecilia Vega (anchor)|Cecilia Vega]]\n*[[CNN]]<ref>https://www.cnn.com/specials/profiles</ref> \u2013 [[Jim Acosta]], Kate Bennett, [[Kaitlan Collins]], Stephen Collinson, [[Jeremy Diamond]], Kevin Liptak, Allie Malloy, [[Jeff Zeleny]] \n*[[CNBC]] \u2013 Eamon Javers<ref>https://twitter.com/EamonJavers</ref>, [[Kayla Tausche]], Christina Wilkie<ref>https://twitter.com/christinawilkie</ref>\n*[[Telemundo]] \u2013 Maria Pe\u00f1a<ref>https://twitter.com/mariauxpen</ref>\n*Foreign Press \u2013 Takaaki Abe ([[Nippon TV]]), Gustau Alegret ([[NTN24]])<ref>https://twitter.com/GustauAlegret</ref>, Nadia Bilbassy ([[Al Arabiya]])<ref>https://twitter.com/nadia_bilbassy</ref>, Ching-Yi Chang ([[Shanghai Media Group]]), Philip Crowther ([[France 24]])<ref>https://twitter.com/PhilipinDC</ref>, Peter Kleim ([[n-tv]]), Raquel Kr\u00e4henb\u00fchl ([[GloboNews]])<ref>https://twitter.com/Rkrahenbuhl</ref>, [[Richard Latendresse]] ([[TVA Group]]), Cordelia Lynch ([[Sky News]])<ref>https://twitter.com/CordeliaSkyNews</ref>, [[Joy Malbon]] ([[CTV News]])\n*Regional Press \u2013 [[Scott Thuman]] ([[Sinclair Broadcast Group]])\n*[[PBS]] \u2013 [[Yamiche Alcindor]]\n*[[Al Jazeera English]] \u2013 [[Alan Fisher (broadcast journalist)|Alan Fisher]], [[Kimberly Halkett]]\n*[[Newsmax TV]] \u2013 Emerald Robinson<ref>https://www.newsmax.com/newsfront/newsmax-tv-emerald-robinson-media-white-house-correspondent/2020/02/11/id/953545/</ref>, John Gizzi<ref>https://twitter.com/johngizzi?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor</ref>\n*[[Christian Broadcasting Network]] \u2013 [[David Brody (correspondent)|David Brody]], Jennifer Wishon<ref>https://twitter.com/JenniferWishon</ref>\n*[[Univision]] \u2013 Janet Rodriguez<ref>https://twitter.com/janrodrigueztv</ref>, Fernando Pizarro<ref>https://twitter.com/FPizarro_DC</ref>\n*[[BBC World News]] \u2013 [[Jon Sopel]], [[Tara McKelvey]]\n*[[One America News Network]] \u2013 [[Chanel Rion]]\n*[[C-SPAN]] \u2013 Sean Doody<ref>https://twitter.com/swdoody</ref>, Victor Montoro<ref>https://twitter.com/vmontoroCSPAN</